{"vocabInfos":[{"lsjDefs":"<b> τεῖχος</b>, εος, τό, <br /> <b>wall</b>, especially <b>city-wall</b>, Ἰλιόφι κλυτὰ τείχεα [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 21.295, compare 446, 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 6.9, +others\">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; of the <b>embankment</b> round the ships, τάφρος Δαναῶν καὶ τ. ὕπερθεν [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 12.4, compare 25ff; τ. ἐς ἀμφίχυτον (of heapedup earth) 20.145 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; Κιμμέρια τ. <b>earthworks</b>, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 4.12; but τ. λάϊνα 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Troades” 1087 (Lyric poetry), compare 5th c.BC: Thucydides Historicus 1.93, etc.; λίθοις οὓς ἔλιπον εἰς τὸ τ. ἀναλίσκοντες “IG” 12.81.9 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; ξύλινον τεῖχος exceptionally, Oracle texts cited in [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 7.141, compare 8.51, 9.65, 5th c.BC: Thucydides Historicus 2.75, 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “Historia Graeca (Hellenica)” 1.3.4, Oracle texts cited in 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Equites” 1040 (5th c.BC: Pindarus Lyricus \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>] uses this phrase for <b>a funeral pile, </b> “P.” 3.38); τ. χάλκεον [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 10.3 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; τ. σιδηροῦν, τείχη χαλκᾶ καὶ ἀδαμάντινα, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Equites” 1046, 4th c.BC: Aeschines Orator 3.84 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; τειχέων κιθῶνες coats <b>of walls</b>, i.e. walls one within the other, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 7.139 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; τεῖχος ἐλαύνειν, see at {ἐλαύνω} [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 111.2; τ. ἔδειμαν 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 7.436; οἰκοδομέειν 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 1.98, compare 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Aves” 1132, etc. (τ. οἰκοδομήσασθαι\">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>] to build oneself <b>walls</b>, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Thucydides Historicus 7.11); τ. ἄξειν [prev. author] 6.99; τὰ τ. στῆσαι 4th c.BC: Demosthenes Orator 20.74; τ. περιβάλλειν ταῖς πόλεσι 4th c.BC: Aristoteles Philosophus “Politica” 1331a3 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; τ. περιβαλέσθαι build <b>walls</b> round one's city, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 1.141, compare 5th c.BC: Thucydides Historicus 1.8, etc. (also τ. περιβαλέσθαι τὴν πόλιν 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 1.163:\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>] —hence _passive_, τεῖχος περιβεβλημένος having a <b>wall</b> round it, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Theaetetus” 174e \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; τείχη περιβεβλημένοι, of citizens, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th c.BC: Aristoteles Philosophus “Politica” 1331a8)\">Refs 4th c.BC+</a>]; but also νῆσον περιβάλλεσθαι τείχει surround one's island with <b>walls</b>, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Critias” 116a \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; τ. ῥήξασθαι breach the <b>wall</b>, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 12.90, compare 257; τεῖχος ἀναρρήξας 7.461 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; so in Prose, τ. διαιρεῖν, περιαιρέειν, κατελεῖν κατασκάψαι, etc., [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Thucydides Historicus 2.75, 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 6.46, 48, 5th c.BC: Thucydides Historicus 4.109, etc. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__2</b></Level3> τὰ μακρὰ τ., at Athens, lines of wall connecting the city-wall (ὁ περίβολος) and the harbours, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Thucydides Historicus 2.13 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; they were called respectively τὸ βόρειον or Peiraic, and τὸ νότιον or Phaleric wall [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\"(5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Respublica” 439e, 4th c.BC: Aeschines Orator 2.173, 174), compare σκέλος 11: an intermediate wall (τὸ διὰ μέσου τ. 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Gorgias” 455e) ran parallel to the northern, which was therefore called also τὸ ἔξωθεν, 5th c.BC: Thucydides Historicus 2.13: the quarter inside the walls is sometimes called τὸ μακρὸν τ\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]. <b>Long Wall</b>, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Andocides Orator 1.45. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level2><b>__II</b></Level2> <b>fortification, castle, fort</b>, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Pindarus Lyricus “Fragmenta.” 213, 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 3.14, 91, etc. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level2><b>__III</b></Level2> <b>walled, fortified town</b> or <b>city</b>, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" [prev. author] 9.41, 115, 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “Institutio Cyri (Cyropaedia)” 7.5.13, etc. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level2><b>__IV</b></Level2> <b>wall</b> of a temple, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" “PEleph.” 20.52 (3rd c.BC)\">Refs 3rd c.BC+</a>]; of a house, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" “PHamb.” 15.8 (3rd c.AD), “PStrassb.” 9.8 (4th c.AD)\">Refs 3rd c.AD+</a>], etc. (Cf. Sanskrit <i>dehmi</i> 'anoint, smear, plaster', Gothic <i>digan</i> 'mould, create (= πλάσσω)', <b>daigs</b> 'dough', Latin <i>fingo</i>, <b>figura</b>, Osc. <b>feihúss</b> 'walls', etc.)","strongNumber":"G5038","accentedUnicode":"τεῖχος","shortDef":"wall","mediumDef":"<b>a wall</b>, of a city, <ref='Act.9.25'>Acts 9:25;</ref> <ref='2Co.11.33'>2Cor. 11:33;</ref> <ref='Heb.11.30'>Heb. 11:30;</ref> <ref='Rev.21.12, 14'>Rev. 21:12, 14</ref>f., 17-19*","stepGloss":"wall","stepTransliteration":"teichos","count":9,"_es_Definition":"muro, muralla","_zh_tw_Definition":"牆, 特別指城牆","_zh_Definition":"墙, 特别指城墙","_step_Type":"word","_vi_Definition":"tường thành; vách thành","_zh_tw_Gloss":"牆","_es_Gloss":"muro","_zh_Gloss":"墙"}]}